## Understanding RSS Feed Architecture

RSS feeds operate on a publisher-subscriber model where websites publish standardized XML files containing recent content, and subscribers (like Readwise Reader) periodically check these files for updates. Each feed contains metadata about articles including title, publication date, summary, and full content or link to the original. The quality of your RSS workflow depends heavily on feed discovery—many sites make their feeds obvious, but others hide them behind obscure URLs or require digging into page source.

## Feed Discovery Strategies

Effective feed discovery involves multiple approaches. Look for the orange RSS icon in browser address bars, which indicates a detectable feed. Many sites publish feeds at predictable URL patterns like /feed, /rss, /atom.xml, or /feed.xml. For sites without obvious feeds, tools like Feedburner, Feedity, or FiveTone can generate feeds from non-RSS websites. When subscribing to newsletters, check if the publisher offers an RSS version of their email content—many do at alternative URLs.

## Organizing for Optimal Retrieval

The organization scheme you choose dramatically affects how usable your feed collection becomes. Create topic-based folders that mirror your areas of interest or professional domains: Technology, Science, Industry News, Personal Development, etc. Within these folders, implement a three-tier priority system: essential feeds checked daily, interesting feeds checked every few days, and archive feeds checked weekly. This tiered approach prevents overwhelm while ensuring you catch important content. Tag individual articles during reading rather than over-organizing feeds—flexibility beats rigid structure.

## Feed Refresh Mechanics

Readwise Reader manages feed refresh through polling intervals you configure per-feed or globally. Freshness requirements vary by feed type: breaking news sources need hourly refreshes, while weekly blog posts only need daily checks. Be aware that aggressive refreshing strains server resources and may get your accounts rate-limited or temporarily blocked. The sweet spot for most feeds is 2-4 hours for high-priority sources and 6-12 hours for standard subscriptions. Some feeds offer push alternatives through PubSubHubbub, which notifies subscribers of updates rather than requiring polling.

## Handling Paywalled and Partial Content

Many premium publications gate their best content behind paywalls, and RSS feeds often deliver only excerpts or metadata. Strategies for handling this include subscribing to the full feed when available (some sites offer separate premium RSS feeds), using browser extensions that follow paywall bypasses legally, maintaining browser tabs to complete reading later when you have access, or flagging articles for follow-up reading. Some users maintain spreadsheet logs of paywalled articles they want to revisit with free trial access or library subscriptions. Understanding each source's content policy helps you set realistic expectations about what RSS will deliver.

## Notification Management

RSS notifications serve different purposes than social media notifications—they're pull-based rather than push-based, meaning you check them on your schedule. Configure notifications to summarize new content daily rather than per-article to reduce interruption fatigue. Many users benefit from batching all feed updates into a morning reading session rather than real-time alerts. Reserve instant notifications for feeds where timeliness is critical, such as security advisories or breaking news from trusted sources.

## Code Examples

### Example 1

```bash
#!/bin/bash
# Feed discovery script - checks common feed URL patterns

WEBSITE="example.com"

check_feed() {
    local url=$1
    local status=$(curl -s -o /dev/null -w "%{http_code}" --max-time 10 "$url")
    if [ "$status" == "200" ]; then
        echo "FOUND: $url"
    fi
}

echo "Checking common feed paths for $WEBSITE..."

check_feed "https://$WEBSITE/feed"
check_feed "https://$WEBSITE/feed/"
check_feed "https://$WEBSITE/feed.xml"
check_feed "https://$WEBSITE/rss"
check_feed "https://$WEBSITE/rss.xml"
check_feed "https://$WEBSITE/atom.xml"
check_feed "https://$WEBSITE/index.xml"
check_feed "https://www.$WEBSITE/feed"
check_feed "https://blog.$WEBSITE/feed"
check_feed "https://$WEBSITE/feed/rss"

echo "Discovery complete."
```

### Example 2

```python
import feedparser
from datetime import datetime

def parse_feed(url):
    feed = feedparser.parse(url)

    print(f"Feed Title: {feed.feed.title}")
    print(f"Feed Description: {feed.feed.description}")
    print(f"Number of Entries: {len(feed.entries)}")
    print("-" * 50)

    articles = []
    for entry in feed.entries[:10]:
        article = {
            'title': entry.get('title', 'No title'),
            'link': entry.get('link', 'No link'),
            'published': entry.get('published', 'Unknown date'),
            'summary': entry.get('summary', '')[:200] + '...' if entry.get('summary') else 'No summary'
        }
        articles.append(article)

        print(f"Title: {article['title']}")
        print(f"Published: {article['published']}")
        print(f"Summary: {article['summary']}")
        print()

    return articles

# Example usage
if __name__ == "__main__":
    test_feed = "https://feeds.bbci.co.uk/news/rss.xml"
    articles = parse_feed(test_feed)
    print(f"Parsed {len(articles)} articles successfully.")
```

### Example 3

```python
import xml.etree.ElementTree as ET
import json

def opml_to_json(opml_file):
    tree = ET.parse(opml_file)
    root = tree.getroot()

    feeds = []
    categories = {}

    for outline in root.iter('outline'):
        xml_url = outline.get('xmlUrl')
        if xml_url:
            feed = {
                'title': outline.get('text', 'Untitled'),
                'xmlUrl': xml_url,
                'htmlUrl': outline.get('htmlUrl', ''),
                'category': outline.get('category', 'Uncategorized')
            }
            feeds.append(feed)

            if feed['category'] not in categories:
                categories[feed['category']] = []
            categories[feed['category']].append(feed['title'])

    result = {
        'total_feeds': len(feeds),
        'feeds': feeds,
        'categories': categories
    }

    return result

# Example usage
if __name__ == "__main__":
    # This would read an actual OPML file
    # result = opml_to_json('subscriptions.opml')
    # print(json.dumps(result, indent=2))

    print("Usage: result = opml_to_json('your_subscriptions.opml')")
    print("This extracts all feed URLs and organizes by category")
```

