<opml version="2.0">
  <head>
    <title>My RSS Subscriptions</title>
    <dateCreated>2024-01-15T10:00:00Z</dateCreated>
  </head>
  <body>
    <outline text="Technology" title="Technology">
      <outline type="rss" text="TechCrunch" title="TechCrunch" xmlUrl="https://techcrunch.com/feed/"/>
      <outline type="rss" text="Ars Technica" title="Ars Technica" xmlUrl="https://feeds.arstechnica.com/arstechnica/index"/>
      <outline type="rss" text="Wired" title="Wired" xmlUrl="https://www.wired.com/feed/rss"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Science" title="Science">
      <outline type="rss" text="Nature" title="Nature" xmlUrl="https://www.nature.com/nature.rss"/>
      <outline type="rss" text="Quanta Magazine" title="Quanta Magazine" xmlUrl="https://www.quantamagazine.org/feed/"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Productivity" title="Productivity">
      <outline type="rss" text="James Clear" title="James Clear" xmlUrl="https://jamesclear.com/feed"/>
    </outline>
  </body>
</opml>
```

### Example 5

```javascript
async function validateFeed(url) {
    const issues = [];
    const warnings = [];

    try {
        const response = await fetch(url, {
            method: 'HEAD',
            headers: { 'Accept': 'application/rss+xml, application/xml, text/xml' }
        });

        const contentType = response.headers.get('Content-Type');

        if (!response.ok) {
            issues.push(`HTTP ${response.status}: ${response.statusText}`);
        }

        if (contentType && !contentType.includes('xml') && !contentType.includes('rss')) {
            warnings.push(`Content-Type is ${contentType}, may not be valid RSS`);
        }

        const allowedTypes = ['200', '301', '302'];
        if (!allowedTypes.includes(String(response.status))) {
            issues.push(`Unexpected status code: ${response.status}`);
        }

    } catch (error) {
        issues.push(`Fetch failed: ${error.message}`);
    }

    return {
        url,
        valid: issues.length === 0,
        issues,
        warnings
    };
}

// Example usage with multiple feeds
const testFeeds = [
    'https://example.com/valid-feed.xml',
    'https://example.com/broken-feed.xml',
    'https://example.com/missing-feed.xml'
];

async function validateAllFeeds(feeds) {
    const results = await Promise.all(feeds.map(url => validateFeed(url)));
    results.forEach(result => {
        console.log(`${result.valid ? '✓' : '✗'} ${result.url}`);
        result.issues.forEach(issue => console.log(`  Issue: ${issue}`));
        result.warnings.forEach(warning => console.log(`  Warning: ${warning}`));
    });
    return results;
}

// validateAllFeeds(testFeeds);
```



## Common Mistakes

- Subscribing to too many feeds without proper organization leads to feed overwhelm and abandonment of the system entirely
- Setting refresh intervals too aggressive causes rate limiting or IP blocking from feed sources
- Ignoring feed URL changes when websites restructure their content management systems, resulting in missed updates
- Relying on feed proxies without understanding their limitations can expose your reading habits to third parties
- Not deduplicating feeds when sources publish identical content across multiple feed formats


## Best Practices

- Maintain a spreadsheet or document tracking all feed sources, their URLs, categories, and last verification date
- Use a dedicated email address for feed-related subscriptions to separate professional and personal reading streams
- Schedule regular feed audits monthly to remove inactive feeds, consolidate duplicates, and discover new sources
- Implement a read-later-first workflow: save interesting articles without reading immediately, process in batches
- Export OPML backups regularly before major changes or migrations to prevent subscription loss

